# Enable Optimizations Here
## Sage attention and Torch Compile
- If your environment supports these.
## Normalized Attention Guidance (**NAG**)
- For negative prompting at CFG=1.
## Lightx2v 
- For fewer inference steps at the expense of motion quality. 
- The lightx2v loras can also amplify VACE's tendency to cause color or brightness shifts in generated frames.
- For best results, don't use the lora. Run with regular Wan settings (20 steps, CFG=3.5, shift=8, or thereabouts. YMMV.)
- Select your high and low lora files in the widgets here.
- Set the lora strengths. This is a balancing act. 
  - Strength too low=poor transition between clips (blur, ghosting). 
  - Strength too high=VACE clip is too bright.

nodes.title: Batching the output filenames
widgets_values:
ComfyUI's caching skips nodes that produce the same output as the previous iteration. By connecting the Video Combine filenames (which change each iteration) to For Loop End, we ensure 
the workflow runs completely every time. 

The filenames aren't actually used, they're just present to keep things moving.

nodes.title: How To Use This Workflow
widgets_values:
# How to Use This Workflow
## The purpose of this workflow is to generate transition frames between two or more input videos.
### This smooths out sudden motion shifts between clips and replaces noisy frames that sometimes appear at clip endings.

---
## IMPORTANT: Before running this workflow, you must configure it for your system. What works for my system probably doesn't work for yours. Please read the green notes for guidance.

For initial setup and basic configuration, you should only need to interact with the two nearby groups, ***Configuration*** and ***Model Load and Inference***.

---

### 1. Select models appropriate for your system
In the **Load Wan Models** node to the right, select your VACE models. Choose models that match what you usually run in your normal Wan workflow. If you usually run FP8 for video generation, choose FP8 here. If you usually use Q4 GGUF, select GGUF.

### 2. Configure the KSamplers and Optimizations
Next to the model load subgraph is the sampler subgraph. You can toggle common optimizations here, like lightx2v, sage attention and torch compile, or you can open the subgraph and work directly with these options. In the subgraph you can also change KSampler settings to your liking. As with the model choice, try to match the sampler settings and optimizations that you normally use for Wan generation. 

### 3. Clean up from previous runs
- **Clear ComfyUI's run cache.** It's important to clear the execution cache between runs if you have run the workflow fully or partially already. Failure to do this will cause ComfyUI to skip steps that it has cached. Go to *C -> Edit -> Unload Models and Execution Cache*. You may also have a button next to **Manager** on your top button bar that does this.
- **Delete or rename existing `vace-work` directory**. If you're re-running, don't leave previous work files in your project directory or they'll be included in your final video.

### 4. Prepare inputs
Your input videos should be placed in an empty directory and named such that they'll sort in the order they're meant to be viewed. e.g. `video01.mp4`, `video02.mp4`, etc. *Use zero-padding in your file names to avoid issues from lexical sorting.* If your files are named `video1.mp4`, `video9.mp4`, `video10.mp4`, they'll get sorted to `video1.mp4`, `video10.mp4`, `video9.mp4`, which is probably not what you want. Naming them `video01.mp4`, `video09.mp4`, `video10.mp4` will force correct sort order.

### 5. Set the workflow parameters
See above for details on parameters.

### 6. Run the workflow
- This version uses a For Loop node to iterate over your input files, so queuing it multiple times is not necessary as it was in previous versions. I'm not yet fully convinced that this is a good idea, but for now it seems stable enough. I'd like to hear about any issues you encounter with this loop implementation.
- After frame generation completes, the final output video will be stitched together and placed in your specified project directory, `ComfyUI/output/[project-directory]`.
- Work files from the run will remain in `ComfyUI/output/[project-directory]/vace-work`. You may safely delete the work directory after a successful run.

nodes.title: Workflow Parameters
widgets_values:
# Parameters

Parameter |Description 
-|-
Input Path | The location of your input files.
Project Name | Output files will be placed in a directory with this name in your ComfyUI output directory. `ComfyUI/output/MyProject`
Context Frames | The number of frames on either side of the transition that VACE will use as references for frame interpolation. 8 is a good value to start with.
Replace Frames | The number of frames to regenerate on each side of the stitch. e.g. If set to 8, then VACE will generate 16 frames; 8 frames at the end of the first video and 8 frames at the start of the second video. This is the number of frames that will be *overwritten* by newly generated frames. Start small, 4 or 8 frames and adjust upward until you like the result.
New Frames | The number of additional frames to generate in addition to `Replace Frames`. Effectively extending the videos from the middle. If you have a reason to set `Replace Frames` to zero, then you'll want to add some frames here.
Prompts | Prompts are optional here. The model is primarily guided by the motion cues in the context frames.


This workflow will generate 
```
(Context Frames * 2) + (Replace Frames * 2) + New Frames + 1
```
 total frames. (The +1 is to meet the Wan's preference for generating 4n+1 frames at a time. If we don't precisely hit that, the model will quietly round down our requested number of frames to the nearest 4n+1.)
The same rules apply here as with regular Wan generations, so 81 total frames is still the sweet spot.

nodes.title: Alternate Sampler Subgraphs
widgets_values:
# Alternate Sampler Setups

## Samplers and model optimizations have been isolated so it's relatively easy to customize or swap configurations without affecting the rest of the workflow.

- Replace the "2 KSampler" node above with one of these, or customize one until it makes you feel good.
- Ideally, the model and sampler setup you use in this workflow should closely resemble whatever setup you use in your normal Wan generation workflow. *Don't assume my defaults will work well on your system!*

nodes.title: âš ï¸  FP8 + MOE/TripleK Samplers + Easy For Loop âš ï¸
widgets_values:
# Bug Alert 
## ComfyUI will crash when running this workflow with FP8 models and the Wan MOE KSampler or the TripleKSampler, unless models are unloaded at the end of each loop iteration.

I can't say why the For Loop causes this problem, or why it only affects FP8 models. But if you're going to run one of these samplers with FP8, be sure to toggle *unload_all_models* in the **VRAM Debug** node in the **Loop End** group. It will have some impact on performance, but it's the only way to run under the aforementioned conditions.

### The batch version of this workflow does not have this problem.

nodes.title: Cross Fade
widgets_values:
# Cross Fade
### The context frames at the start and end of the VACE generation are cross-faded over the original frames.
- This helps to mute the color/brightness shift that VACE can introduce.
- Since context frames in the original videos and the VACE generation are identical except for the color/brightness shift we are addressing, there is no danger of the cross fade introducing ghosting or blur.
- To disable cross fade, open the **Cross Fade Contexts** subgraph and set *start_level* and *end_level* both to 1.00 on the two Cross Fade nodes.

nodes.title: Color Match
widgets_values:
# Color Match
## Match the colors of every VACE-generated frame to the colors of the last context frame from the original video.
I honestly don't know how effective this is, or whether it works at all, but it doesn't seem to do any harm when I enable it. People have suggested that various color match schemes help them with VACE color/brightness shifts, so here is a reference implementation that you can try and alter to fit your needs.

nodes.title: Last Input File
widgets_values:
After the last iteration of the batch, we save the final *replace + context* frames from video2.

On all other iterations, these frames are discarded from video2 until the next iteration, when this video2 will be that iteration's video1, and the frames will be processed then.

nodes.title: OOM at the Last Step?
widgets_values:
If you are running out RAM at the video join step, you can try using the VideoHelperSuite *Meta Batch Manager* node.

Create a new blank workflow and then copy/paste the three nodes below into it. Set the node values:

  - `Load Images (Path).directory` = Full pathname of your output/projectname/vace-work directory. In Windows you can right-click that folder and choose *Copy as path*.

  - `Video Combine.frame_rate` = your input video fps, if other than 16.

  - `Video Combine.filename_prefix` = whatever you want

  - `Meta Batch Manager.frames_per_batch` = some value that won't exhaust all your memory. Small values are safer, but will make the process take longer. Click the question mark icon on the Meta Batch Manager for more information about how it works.

nodes.title: Changelog
widgets_values:
[Github](https://github.com/stuttlepress/ComfyUI-Wan-VACE-Video-Joiner) | [CivitAI](https://civitai.com/models/2024299) 

- **v2.2** *Complexity Reduction Release*
  - Removed fancy model loader which was causing headaches for safetensors users without any gguf models installed, and vice-versa.
  - Removed the MOE KSampler and TripleKSampler subgraphs. You can still use these samplers with this workflow, but it's up to you to bring them and set them up.
  - Custom node dependencies reduced.
  - Un-subgraphed some functions. Sadly, this powerful and useful feature is still too unstable to distribute to users on varying versions of ComfyUI.
- **v2.1**
  - Add Prune Outputs to Video Combine nodes, preventing extra frames from being added to the output  
- **v2.0**
  - Workflow redesign. Core functionality is the same, but hopefully usability is improved
  - (Experimental) Added cross fade at VACE boundaries to mitigate brightness/color shift
  - (Experimental) Added color match for VACE frames to mitigate brightness/color shift
  - Save intermediate work as 16 bit png instead of ffv1
  - Integrated video join into the main workflow. No more need to run the join part separately.
  - Excessive documentation
  - (Experimental) New looping workflow variant that doesn't require manual queueing and index manipulation. 
  - Inputs and outputs are logged to the console for better progress tracking

- **v1.3**
  - removed lingering custom primitive node

- **v1.2**
  - Sort the input directory list.  

- **v1.1**
  - Preserve input framerate in workflow VACE outputs. Previously, all output was forced to 16fps. Note, you must manually set the framerate in the Join & Save output.

nodes.title: First Input File
widgets_values:
This mess determines how many frames we select from the beginning of video1. Either *frame_count - (context_frames+replace_frames)* or *frame_count - (2\*(context_frames+replace_frames))*.

If this is any video other than the first one in the batch, we skip the first (*context + replace*) frames from the video, since they were processed and saved in the previous run of the batch, when video1 was video2.

If we are processing the very first video in the batch (index==0), then we include these initial frames.

nodes.title: Framerate
widgets_values:
It is assumed that video1 and video2 have the same framerates.

Output video will be written with the same framerate as that of video1.
